.TH socket 3 "kernel 10.6.1" "Ericsson AB" "Erlang Module Definition"
.SH NAME
socket \- Socket interface.

.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
This module provides an API for network sockets. Functions are provided to create, delete and manipulate the sockets as well as sending and receiving data on them.

.PP
The intent is that it shall be as "close as possible" to the OS level socket interface. The only significant additions are that some of the functions, e.g. \fIrecv/3\fR, have a time-out argument, and that \fIrecv/*\fR for a \fIstream\fR socket iterates until the requested amount of data has been received.

.RS 4
.PP
\fBNote \fR

.PP
\fBAsynchronous Calls\fR

.PP
Some functions feature \fIasynchronous calls\fR.  This is achieved by setting the \fITimeout\fR argument to \fInowait\fR or to a \fIHandle ::\fR \fIreference/0\fR. See the respective function's type specification. This module has two different implementations of asynchronous calls. One on the \fIUnix\fR family of operating systems: \fIselect\fR - based on the standard socket interface's \fIselect(3)\fR/\fIpoll(3)\fR calls, and one on \fIWindows\fR: \fIcompletion\fR - based on asynchronous I/O Completion Ports. The difference shows in the return values and message formats because they have slightly different semantics.

.PP
\fBThe \fR\fB\fIcompletion\fR\fR\fB and \fR\fB\fIselect\fR\fR\fB Return Values\fR

.PP
For instance, the call \fIrecv(Socket, 0, nowait)\fR, when there is no data available for reading, will, depending on the operating system, return one of:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fI{completion, \fR\fICompletionInfo\fR\fI}\fR

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fI{select, \fR\fISelectInfo\fR\fI}\fR Where \fICompletionInfo\fR is \fI{completion_info, _, \fR\fICompletionHandle\fR\fI}\fR and \fISelectInfo\fR is \fI{select_info, _, \fR\fISelectHandle\fR\fI}\fR. Both the \fICompletionHandle\fR and the \fISelectHandle\fR are of type \fIreference/0\fR. When the operation can continue, a \fIcompletion\fR message containing the \fICompletionHandle\fR or a \fIselect\fR message containing the \fISelectHandle\fR is sent to the calling process. On \fIselect\fR systems, \fIrecv/2,3,4\fR may also return:

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fI{select, {\fR\fISelectInfo\fR\fI, Data}\fR This may happen for sockets of type \fIstream\fR when \fILength > 1\fR since the OS may split a data stream at any point and deliver just the first part of the requested data. For the next \fIrecv/2,3,4\fR call; the \fILength\fR to receive will probably have to be adjusted due to the already delivered data in this return value. On \fIselect\fR systems, when the \fI{otp, select_read}\fR option is \fItrue\fR, the asynchronous \fIrecv/3,4\fR, \fIrecvfrom/3,4\fR, and \fIrecvmsg/3,4,5\fR functions may also return:

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fI{select_read, {\fR\fISelectInfo\fR\fI, Data}\fR This indicates that the receive operation was completed; all requested data has been delivered,  and that the calling process will get a \fIselect\fR message when there is data available for the next receive operation.

.PP
\fBThe \fR\fB\fIcompletion\fR\fR\fB and \fR\fB\fIselect\fR\fR\fB Messages \fR

.PP
The \fIcompletion\fR message has the format:

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fI{'$socket', \fR\fISocket\fR\fI, completion, {\fR\fICompletionHandle\fR\fI, CompletionStatus}}\fR The \fIselect\fR message has the format:

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fI{'$socket', \fR\fISocket\fR\fI, select, \fR\fISelectHandle\fR\fI}\fR When a \fIcompletion\fR message is received (which contains the \fIresult\fR of the operation), it means that the operation has been \fIcompleted\fR and \fICompletionStatus\fR is the return value for the operation, which is what the function that initiated the operation could have returned, with the \fInowait\fR argument, except for the \fIcompletion\fR and \fIselect\fR return values. When a \fIselect\fR message is received, it only means that the operation \fImay now continue\fR, by retrying the operation (which may return a new \fI{select, _}\fR value).  Some operations are retried by repeating the same function call, and some have a dedicated function variant to be used for the retry.  See the respective function's documentation.

.PP
\fBOperation Queuing on \fR\fB\fIselect\fR\fR\fB Systems\fR

.PP
On \fIselect\fR systems, all other processes are \fIlocked out\fR until the current process has completed the operation as in a continuation call has returned a value indicating success or failure (not a \fIselect\fR or \fIselect_read\fR return).  Other processes are queued and get a \fIselect\fR return which makes them wait for their turn. Note that receiving data from parallel processes is only suitable for some protocols.  For a \fIstream\fR socket it is in general a recipe for disaster.

.PP
\fBCancelling an operation\fR

.PP
An operation that is in progress (not completed) may be canceled using \fIcancel/2\fR both on \fIcompletion\fR and \fIselect\fR systems. Cancelling an operation ensures that there is no \fIcompletion\fR, \fIselect\fR, nor \fIabort\fR message in the inbox after the \fIcancel/2\fR call.

.PP
\fBUsing a \fR\fB\fIHandle\fR\fR

.PP
If creating a \fIreference/0\fR with \fImake_ref()\fR and using that as the \fITimeout | Handle\fR argument, the same \fIHandle\fR will then be the \fISelectHandle\fR in the returned \fIselect_info/0\fR and the received \fIselect\fR message, or be the \fICompletionHandle\fR in the returned \fIcompletion_info/0\fR and the received \fIcompletion\fR message. The compiler may then optimize a following \fIreceive\fR statement to only scan the messages that arrive after the \fIreference/0\fR is created.  If the message queue is large this is a big optimization. It is not possible to have more than one operation in progress with the same \fIreference/0\fR.

.PP
\fBRepeating an Operation on a \fR\fB\fIselect\fR\fR\fB Systems\fR

.PP
On\fIselect\fR systems, if a call would be repeated \fIbefore\fR the \fIselect\fR message has been received it replaces the operation in progress:

.IP
.nf
  {select, {select_info, Handle}} = socket:accept(LSock, nowait),
  {ok, Socket} = socket:accept(LSock, 1000),
  :

.fi

.PP
Above, \fIHandle\fR is \fIno longer\fR valid once the second \fIaccept/2\fR, call has been made (the first call is automatically canceled). After the second \fIaccept/2\fR call returns, the accept operation has completed. Note that there is a race here; there is no way to know if the call is repeated \fIbefore\fR the \fIselect\fR message is sent since it \fImay\fR have been sent just before the repeated call.  So now there might be a \fIselect\fR message containing \fIHandle\fR in the inbox.

.PP
\fBThe \fR\fB\fIabort\fR\fR\fB Message\fR

.PP
Another message the user must be prepared for (when using \fInowait | Handle\fR) is the \fIabort\fR message:

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fI{'$socket', \fR\fISocket\fR\fI, abort, Info}\fR This message indicates that the operation in progress has been aborted. For instance, if the socket has been closed by another process; \fIInfo\fR will be \fI{Handle, closed}\fR.

.RE

.RE

