.RE
.B
\fBotp_socket_option() ::\fR
\fB          debug | iow | controlling_process | rcvbuf | rcvctrlbuf |\fR
\fB          sndctrlbuf | select_read | meta | use_registry | fd | domain.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Protocol level \fIotp\fR socket option.

.PP
Socket options for the \fIotp\fR pseudo protocol level, that is: \fI{otp, Name}\fR options.

.PP
This protocol level is the Erlang/OTP's socket implementation layer, hence above all OS protocol levels.

debug
.RS 2

\fIboolean/0\fR - Activate debug logging.

.RE

iow
.RS 2

\fIboolean/0\fR - Inform On Wrap of statistics counters.

.RE

controlling_process
.RS 2

\fIpid/0\fR - The socket "owner". Only the current controlling process can set this option.

.RE

rcvbuf
.RS 2

\fIBufSize :: (default | integer()>0) | {N :: integer()>0, BufSize :: (default | integer()>0)} \fR- Receive buffer size.
.PP
The value \fIdefault\fR is only valid to \fIset\fR.

.PP
\fIN\fR specifies the number of read attempts to do in a tight loop before assuming no more data is pending.

.PP
This is the allocation size for the receive buffer used when calling the OS protocol stack's receive API, when no specific size (size 0) is requested. When the receive function returns the receive buffer is reallocated to the actually received size. If the data is copied or shrunk in place is up to the allocator, and can to some extent be configured in the Erlang VM.

.PP
The similar socket option; \fI{socket,rcvbuf}\fR is a related option for the OS' protocol stack that on Unix corresponds to \fISOL_SOCKET,SO_RCVBUF\fR.


.RE

rcvctrlbuf
.RS 2

\fIBufSize :: (default | integer()>0) \fR- Allocation size for the ancillary data buffer used when calling the OS protocol stack's receive API.
.PP
The value \fIdefault\fR is only valid to \fIset\fR.


.RE

sndctrlbuf
.RS 2

\fIBufSize :: (default | integer()>0) \fR- Allocation size for the ancillary data buffer used when calling the OS protocol stack's sendmsg API.
.PP
The value \fIdefault\fR is only valid to \fIset\fR.

.PP
It is the user's responsibility to set a buffer size that has room for the encoded ancillary data in the message to send.

.PP
See sendmsg and also the \fIctrl\fR field of the \fImsg_send/0\fR type.


.RE

select_read
.RS 2

\fIboolean/0\fR - On \fIselect\fR implementations, see Asynchronous Calls, automatically activate select after a completed read.
.PP
Instead of \fI{ok, Data}\fR the receive operation returns \fI{select_read, {SelectInfo, Data}}\fR, and the calling process can wait for a \fIselect\fR message containing \fISelectInfo\fR when there is data available again.

.PP
Setting this option locks out other processes from receiving any data since the current process continues its operation, so it effectively disables receive operation queuing.


.RE

fd
.RS 2

\fIinteger/0\fR - Only valid to \fIget\fR. The OS protocol levels' socket descriptor. Functions \fIopen/1,2\fR can be used to create a socket according to this module from an existing OS socket descriptor.

.RE

use_registry
.RS 2

\fIboolean/0\fR - Only valid to \fIget\fR. The value is set when the socket is created with \fIopen/2\fR or \fIopen/4\fR.

.RE

.PP
Options not described here are intentionally undocumented and for Erlang/OTP internal use only.


