.RE
.B
\fBprotocol() :: atom().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Protocol name.

.PP
A lowercase \fIatom/0\fR representing an OS protocol name. To be used for example in \fIsocket_option/0\fR in control messages.

.PP
They have the following names in the OS header files:

ip
.RS 2

\fIIPPROTO_IP\fR a.k.a \fISOL_IP\fR with options named \fIIP_\fR*.

.RE

ipv6
.RS 2

\fIIPPROTO_IPV6\fR a.k.a \fISOL_IPV6\fR with options named \fIIPV6_\fR*.

.RE

tcp
.RS 2

\fIIPPROTO_TCP\fR with options named \fITCP_\fR*.

.RE

mptcp
.RS 2

\fIIPPROTO_MPTCP\fR with a few options named \fIMPTCP_\fR*. Most \fITCP_\fR* options apply which is the purpose of Multi-Path TCP.

.RE

udp
.RS 2

\fIIPPROTO_UDP\fR with options named \fIUDP_\fR*.

.RE

sctp
.RS 2

\fIIPPROTO_SCTP\fR with options named \fISCTP_\fR*.

.RE

.PP
There are many other possible protocols, but the ones above are those for which this socket library implements socket options and/or control messages.

.PP
All protocols known to the OS are enumerated when the Erlang VM is started, through the \fIC\fR library call \fIgetprotoent()\fR. See the OS man page for protocols(5). Those in the list above are valid if supported by the platform, even if they aren't enumerated.

.PP
The calls \fIis_supported(ipv6)\fR , \fIis_supported(sctp)\fR  and \fIis_supported(mptcp)\fR  can be used to find out if the protocols \fIipv6\fR, \fIsctp\fR and \fImptcp\fR are supported on the platform as in; appropriate header file and libraries exist.

.PP
The call \fIis_supported(protocols, Protocol)\fR  can only be used to find out if the platform knows the protocol number for a named \fIProtocol\fR.

.PP
See \fIopen/2,3,4\fR


