.SH FUNCTIONS
.LP
.B
\fBaccept(ListenSocket) -> Result\fR
\fB                when\fR
\fB                    Result :: {ok, Socket} | {error, Reason},\fR
\fB                    ListenSocket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                    Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                    Reason :: dynamic().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Equivalent to \fIaccept(ListenSocket, infinity)\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBaccept(ListenSocket, Timeout :: infinity) ->\fR
\fB                {ok, Socket} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                when\fR
\fB                    ListenSocket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                    Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                    Reason ::\fR
\fB                        posix() |\fR
\fB                        closed |\fR
\fB                        invalid() |\fR
\fB                        {create_accept_socket, posix()} |\fR
\fB                        {add_socket, posix()} |\fR
\fB                        {update_accept_context, posix()};\fR
\fB            (ListenSocket, Timeout :: non_neg_integer()) ->\fR
\fB                {ok, Socket} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                when\fR
\fB                    ListenSocket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                    Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                    Reason ::\fR
\fB                        posix() |\fR
\fB                        closed |\fR
\fB                        invalid() |\fR
\fB                        timeout |\fR
\fB                        {create_accept_socket, posix()} |\fR
\fB                        {add_socket, posix()} |\fR
\fB                        {update_accept_context, posix()};\fR
\fB            (ListenSocket,\fR
\fB             nowait | (Handle :: select_handle() | completion_handle())) ->\fR
\fB                {ok, Socket} |\fR
\fB                {select, SelectInfo} |\fR
\fB                {completion, CompletionInfo} |\fR
\fB                {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                when\fR
\fB                    ListenSocket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                    Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                    SelectInfo :: select_info(),\fR
\fB                    CompletionInfo :: completion_info(),\fR
\fB                    Reason ::\fR
\fB                        posix() |\fR
\fB                        closed |\fR
\fB                        invalid() |\fR
\fB                        {create_accept_socket, posix()} |\fR
\fB                        {add_accept_socket, posix()} |\fR
\fB                        {update_accept_context, posix()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Accept a connection on a listening socket.

.PP
\fIListenSocket\fR has to be of a connection oriented type (types \fIstream\fR or \fIseqpacket\fR, see \fIopen/1\fR), and set to listen (see \fIlisten/1\fR).

.PP
If the \fITimeout\fR argument is \fIinfinity\fR; accepts the first pending incoming connection for the listen socket or wait for one to arrive, and return the new connection socket.

.PP
If the \fITimeout\fR argument is a time-out value (\fInon_neg_integer/0\fR); returns \fI{error, timeout}\fR if no connection has arrived after \fITimeout\fR milliseconds.

.PP
If the \fIHandle\fR argument \fInowait\fR \fI(since OTP 22.1)\fR, starts an asynchronous call if the operation couldn't be completed immediately.

.PP
If the \fIHandle\fR argument is a \fIselect_handle/0\fR, \fI(since OTP 24.0)\fR, or on \fIWindows\fR, the equivalent \fIcompletion_handle/0\fR \fI(since OTP 26.0)\fR, starts an asynchronous call like for \fInowait\fR.

.PP
The possible values for \fICompletionStatus\fR in the completion message are:

{ok, NewSocket}
.RS 2
Success; A connection has been accepted.


.RE
{error, Reason}
.RS 2
An error occured and no connection was established.


.RE

.PP
See the note Asynchronous Calls at the start of this module reference manual page.


.RE
.B
\fBbind(Socket, Addr) -> ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB              when\fR
\fB                  Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                  Addr :: sockaddr() | any | broadcast | loopback,\fR
\fB                  Reason :: posix() | closed | invalid().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Bind a name to a socket.

.PP
When a socket is created (with \fIopen\fR), it has no address assigned to it. \fIbind\fR assigns the address specified by the \fIAddr\fR argument.

.PP
The rules used for name binding vary between domains.

.PP
If you bind a socket to an address in for example the \fIinet\fR or \fIinet6\fR address families, with an ephemeral port number (\fI0\fR), and want to know which port that was chosen, you can find out using something like: \fI{ok, #{port := Port}} =\fR\fIsocket:sockname(Socket)\fR


.RE
.B
\fBbind(Socket, Addrs, Action) -> ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB              when\fR
\fB                  Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                  Addrs ::\fR
\fB                      [sockaddr_in()] | [sockaddr_in() | sockaddr_in6()],\fR
\fB                  Action :: add | remove,\fR
\fB                  Reason :: posix() | closed.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Bind a list of socket addreses to a socket.

.PP
When a socket is created (with \fIopen\fR), it has no address assigned to it. This \fIbind\fR assigns the address specified by the \fIAddr\fR argument.

.PP
Calling this function is only valid if the socket is \fItype\fR  = \fIseqpacket\fR and \fIprotocol\fR = \fIsctp\fR.

.PP
If the domain is inet, then all addresses \fImust\fR be IPv4. If the domain is inet6, the addresses can be \fIeither\fR IPv4 or IPv6.


.RE
.B
\fBcancel(Socket, SelectInfo | CompletionInfo) ->\fR
\fB                ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                when\fR
\fB                    Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                    SelectInfo :: select_info(),\fR
\fB                    CompletionInfo :: completion_info(),\fR
\fB                    Reason :: closed | invalid().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Cancel an asynchronous call in progress.

.PP
Call this function to cancel an asynchronous call in progress, that is; it returned a value containing a \fIcompletion_info/0\fR or \fIselect_info/0\fR.

.PP
See the note Asynchronous Calls at the start of this module reference manual page.

.PP
If another process tries an operation of the same basic type (\fIaccept/1\fR | \fIsend/2\fR | \fIrecv/2\fR) it will be enqueued and notified through a \fIselect\fR or \fIcompletion\fR message when the current operation and all enqueued before it has been completed. If the current operation is canceled by this function it is treated as a completed operation; the process first in queue is notified.

.PP
If \fISelectInfo\fR \fI|\fR \fICompletionInfo\fR does not match an operation in progress for the calling process, this function returns \fI{error, {invalid, SelectInfo | CompletionInfo}}\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBcancel_monitor(MRef :: reference()) -> boolean().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Cancel a socket monitor.

.PP
If \fIMRef\fR is a reference that the calling process obtained by calling \fImonitor/1\fR, this monitor is removed. If there is no such monitor for the calling process (or MRef doesn't correspond to a monitor), nothing happens.

.PP
The returned value is one of the following:

true
.RS 2
The monitor was found and removed. In this case, no 
\fI'DOWN'\fR message corresponding to this monitor has been delivered and will not be delivered.

.RE

false
.RS 2
The monitor was not found so it couldn't be removed. This might be because the monitor has already triggered and there is a 
\fI'DOWN'\fR message from this monitor in the caller message queue.

.RE


.RE
.B
\fBclose(Socket) -> ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB               when\fR
\fB                   Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                   Reason :: posix() | closed | timeout.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Close a socket.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRNote that for \fIProtocol = tcp\fR (see \fIopen/3\fR), although TCP guarantees that when the other side sees the stream close all data that we sent before closing has been delivered, there is no way for us to know that the other side got all data and the stream close.  All kinds of network and OS issues may obliterate that. To get such a guarantee we need to implement an in-band acknowledge protocol on the connection, or we can use the \fIshutdown\fR function to signal that no more data will be sent and then wait for the other end to close the socket.  Then we will see our read side getting a socket close.  In this way we implement a small acknowledge protocol using \fIshutdown/2\fR.  The other side cannot know that we ever saw the socket close, but in a client/server scenario that is often not relevant.



.RE
.B
\fBconnect(Socket :: socket()) -> ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                 when Reason :: posix() | closed | invalid().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Finalize a \fIconnect/3\fR operation.

.PP
See the note Asynchronous Calls at the start of this module reference manual page.

.PP
On \fIselect\fR systems this function finalizes a connection setup on a socket, after receiving a \fIselect\fR message \fI{'$socket',\fR \fISocket\fR\fI, select, \fR\fISelectHandle\fR\fI}\fR, and returns whether the connection setup was successful or not.

.PP
Instead of calling this function, for backwards compatibility, it is allowed to call \fIconnect/2,3\fR again, but that incurs more overhead since the connect address and time-out argument are processed in vain.

.PP
The call that completes the connect operation, the second call, cannot return a \fIselect\fR return value.


.RE
.B
\fBconnect(Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB              SockAddr :: sockaddr() | [SockAddr :: term()]) ->\fR
\fB                 ok | {error, Reason :: dynamic()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Equivalent to \fIconnect(Socket, SockAddr, infinity)\fR or \fIconnect(Socket, SockAddrs, undefined, infinity)\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBconnect(Socket, SockAddrs, TimeoutOrHandle) ->\fR
\fB                 {ok, AssocId} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                 when\fR
\fB                     Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                     SockAddrs :: [sockaddr_in()] | [sockaddr_in6()],\fR
\fB                     TimeoutOrHandle ::\fR
\fB                         infinity | Timeout | nowait | Handle,\fR
\fB                     Timeout :: non_neg_integer(),\fR
\fB                     Handle :: select_handle(),\fR
\fB                     AssocId :: sctp_assoc_id(),\fR
\fB                     Reason :: posix() | closed | invalid() | already;\fR
\fB             (Socket, SockAddr, Timeout :: infinity) ->\fR
\fB                 ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                 when\fR
\fB                     Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                     SockAddr :: sockaddr(),\fR
\fB                     Reason ::\fR
\fB                         posix() |\fR
\fB                         closed |\fR
\fB                         invalid() |\fR
\fB                         already | not_bound |\fR
\fB                         {add_socket, posix()} |\fR
\fB                         {update_connect_context, posix()};\fR
\fB             (Socket, SockAddr, Timeout :: non_neg_integer()) ->\fR
\fB                 ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                 when\fR
\fB                     Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                     SockAddr :: sockaddr(),\fR
\fB                     Reason ::\fR
\fB                         posix() |\fR
\fB                         closed |\fR
\fB                         invalid() |\fR
\fB                         already | not_bound | timeout |\fR
\fB                         {add_socket, posix()} |\fR
\fB                         {update_connect_context, posix()};\fR
\fB             (Socket, SockAddr, nowait | Handle) ->\fR
\fB                 ok |\fR
\fB                 {select, SelectInfo} |\fR
\fB                 {completion, CompletionInfo} |\fR
\fB                 {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                 when\fR
\fB                     Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                     SockAddr :: sockaddr(),\fR
\fB                     Handle :: select_handle() | completion_handle(),\fR
\fB                     SelectInfo :: select_info(),\fR
\fB                     CompletionInfo :: completion_info(),\fR
\fB                     Reason ::\fR
\fB                         posix() |\fR
\fB                         closed |\fR
\fB                         invalid() |\fR
\fB                         already | not_bound |\fR
\fB                         {add_socket, posix()} |\fR
\fB                         {update_connect_context, posix()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Connect the socket to the given address(s).

.PP
This function connects the socket to the address(s) specified by the \fISockAddr\fR|\fISockAddrs\fR argument.

.PP
If a connection attempt is already in progress (by another process), \fI{error, already}\fR is returned.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fROn \fIWindows\fR the socket has to be \fIbound\fR.


.PP
If the time-out argument (argument 3) is \fIinfinity\fR it is up to the OS implementation to decide when the connection attempt failed and then what to return; probably \fI{error, etimedout}\fR. The OS time-out may be very long.

.PP
If the time-out argument (argument 3) is a time-out value (\fInon_neg_integer/0\fR); return \fI{error, timeout}\fR if the connection hasn't been established within \fITimeout\fR milliseconds.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRNote that when this call has returned \fI{error, timeout}\fR the connection state of the socket is uncertain since the platform's network stack may complete the connection at any time, up to some platform specific time-out. Repeating a connection attempt towards the same address would be ok, but towards a different address could end up with a connection to either address. The safe play is to close the socket and start over. Also note that this applies to cancelling a \fInowait\fR connect call described below.


.PP
If the time-out argument (argument 2) is \fInowait\fR \fI(since OTP 22.1)\fR, start an asynchronous call if the operation couldn't be completed immediately.

.PP
If the time-out argument (argument 2) is a \fIHandle ::\fR \fIselect_handle/0\fR, \fI(since OTP 24.0)\fR, or on \fIWindows\fR, the equivalent \fIHandle ::\fR \fIcompletion_handle/0\fR \fI(since OTP 26.0)\fR, start an asynchronous call like for \fInowait\fR.

.PP
See the note Asynchronous Calls at the start of this module reference manual page.

.PP
After receiving a \fIselect\fR message; call \fIconnect/1\fR to complete the operation.

.PP
If cancelling the operation with \fIcancel/2\fR see the note above about connection time-out.

.PP
The possible values for \fICompletionStatus\fR in the completion message are:

ok
.RS 2
Complete success; A connection has been established.


.RE
{error, Reason}
.RS 2
An error occured and no connection was established.


.RE

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRNote that calling with a list of socket addresses only works for SCTP sockets (type = \fIseqpacket\fR). And that the family of \fIall\fR addresses in the list is either IPv4 (\fIinet\fR) or IPv6 (\fIinet6\fR).



.RE
.B
\fBgetopt(socket(),\fR
\fB             SocketOption :: {Level :: otp, Opt :: otp_socket_option()}) ->\fR
\fB                {ok, Value :: term()} | {error, invalid() | closed};\fR
\fB            (socket(), SocketOption :: socket_option()) ->\fR
\fB                {ok, Value :: term()} |\fR
\fB                {error, posix() | invalid() | closed}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Get the value of a socket option.

.PP
Gets the value of an OS protocol level socket option, or from the \fIotp\fR pseudo protocol level, which is this module's implementation level above the OS protocol levels.

.PP
See the type otp_socket_option()  for a description of the \fIotp\fR protocol level.

.PP
See the type \fIsocket_option/0\fR for which OS protocol level options that this implementation knows about, how they are related to OS option names, and if there are known peculiarities with any of them.

.PP
What options that are valid depends on the OS, and on the kind of socket (\fIdomain/0\fR,\fItype/0\fR and \fIprotocol/0\fR).  See the type \fIsocket_option()\fR and the socket options  chapter in the User's Guide for more info.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRNot all options are valid, nor possible to get, on all platforms. That is, even if this \fIsocket\fR implementation  support an option; it doesn't mean that the underlying OS does.



.RE
.B
\fBgetopt(Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB             SocketOption :: {sctp, get_peer_addr_info},\fR
\fB             OptValue ::\fR
\fB                 #{assoc_id := sctp_assoc_id(), addr := sockaddr()}) ->\fR
\fB                {ok, Value :: sctp_peer_address_info()} |\fR
\fB                {error, posix() | invalid() | closed};\fR
\fB            (Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB             SocketOption :: {sctp, status},\fR
\fB             OptValue :: #{assoc_id := sctp_assoc_id()}) ->\fR
\fB                {ok, Value :: sctp_status()} |\fR
\fB                {error, posix() | invalid() | closed};\fR
\fB            (Socket :: socket(), Level :: level(), Opt :: term()) ->\fR
\fB                {ok, Value :: term()} |\fR
\fB                {error, posix() | invalid() | closed}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Get a socket option, with a specifier (extra input) \fIOptValue\fR.

.PP
This function is used when the option takes an input 'value' argument. We only support this for a limited set of options: \fI{sctp, get_peer_addr_info}\fR and \fI{sctp, status}\fR.

.PP
Some uses of this function is for \fIbackwards compatibility reasons\fR.

.PP
For instance, \fIgetopt(Socket, Level, Opt)\fR is equivalent to \fIgetopt(Socket, {Level, Opt})\fR, or as a special case if \fIOpt = {NativeOpt :: \fR\fIinteger/0\fR\fI, ValueSpec}\fR equivalent to \fIgetopt_native(Socket, {Level, NativeOpt}, ValueSpec)\fR.

.PP
Use \fIgetopt/2\fR or \fIgetopt_native/3\fR instead to handle the option level and name as a single term, and to make the difference between known options and native options clear.


.RE
.B
\fBgetopt_native(socket(),\fR
\fB                    SocketOption ::\fR
\fB                        socket_option() |\fR
\fB                        {Level :: level() | (NativeLevel :: integer()),\fR
\fB                         NativeOpt :: integer()},\fR
\fB                    ValueType :: integer) ->\fR
\fB                       {ok, Value :: integer()} |\fR
\fB                       {error, posix() | invalid() | closed};\fR
\fB                   (socket(),\fR
\fB                    SocketOption ::\fR
\fB                        socket_option() |\fR
\fB                        {Level :: level() | (NativeLevel :: integer()),\fR
\fB                         NativeOpt :: integer()},\fR
\fB                    ValueType :: boolean) ->\fR
\fB                       {ok, Value :: boolean()} |\fR
\fB                       {error, posix() | invalid() | closed};\fR
\fB                   (socket(),\fR
\fB                    SocketOption ::\fR
\fB                        socket_option() |\fR
\fB                        {Level :: level() | (NativeLevel :: integer()),\fR
\fB                         NativeOpt :: integer()},\fR
\fB                    ValueSize :: non_neg_integer()) ->\fR
\fB                       {ok, Value :: binary()} |\fR
\fB                       {error, posix() | invalid() | closed};\fR
\fB                   (socket(),\fR
\fB                    SocketOption ::\fR
\fB                        socket_option() |\fR
\fB                        {Level :: level() | (NativeLevel :: integer()),\fR
\fB                         NativeOpt :: integer()},\fR
\fB                    ValueSpec :: binary()) ->\fR
\fB                       {ok, Value :: binary()} |\fR
\fB                       {error, posix() | invalid() | closed}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Get a "native" socket option.

.PP
Gets a socket option that may be unknown to our implementation, or that has a type not compatible with our implementation, that is; in "native mode".

.PP
The socket option may be specified with an ordinary \fIsocket_option()\fR  tuple, with a known \fILevel = level()\fR  and an integer \fINativeOpt\fR, or with both an integer \fINativeLevel\fR and \fINativeOpt\fR.

.PP
How to decode the option value has to be specified either with \fIValueType\fR, by specifying the \fIValueSize\fR for a \fIbinary/0\fR that will contain the fetched option value, or by specifying a \fIbinary/0\fR \fIValueSpec\fR that will be copied to a buffer for the \fIgetsockopt()\fR call to write the value in which will be returned as a new \fIbinary/0\fR.

.PP
If \fIValueType\fR is \fIinteger\fR a \fIC\fR type \fI(int)\fR will be fetched, if it is \fIboolean\fR a \fIC\fR type \fI(int)\fR will be fetched and converted into a \fIboolean/0\fR according to the \fIC\fR implementation's notion about true and false.

.PP
If an option is valid depends both on the platform and on what kind of socket it is (\fIdomain/0\fR, \fItype/0\fR and \fIprotocol/0\fR).

.PP
The integer values for \fINativeLevel\fR and \fINativeOpt\fR as well as the \fIValue\fR encoding has to be deduced from the header files for the running system.


.RE
.B
\fBi() -> ok.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Print information to the erlang shell in table format for all sockets.

.PP
The information printed for each socket is specified by the default set of \fIinfo_keys/0\fR (all keys).

.PP
The sockets that are printed are all sockets created by this \fIsocket\fR module's implementation.


.RE
.B
\fBi(InfoKeys :: info_keys()) -> ok;\fR
\fB       (Domain :: inet | inet6 | local) -> ok;\fR
\fB       (Proto :: sctp | tcp | udp) -> ok;\fR
\fB       (Type :: dgram | seqpacket | stream) -> ok.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Print information to the erlang shell in table format for all sockets.

.PP
If the argument is a list of \fIinfo_keys/0\fR, print the specified information for all sockets.  See \fIi/0\fR.

.PP
Otherwise the same as \fIi/2\fR with the same first argument and the default information (see \fIi/0\fR).


.RE
.B
\fBi(Domain :: inet | inet6 | local, InfoKeys) -> ok\fR
\fB           when InfoKeys :: info_keys();\fR
\fB       (Proto :: sctp | tcp | udp, InfoKeys) -> ok\fR
\fB           when InfoKeys :: info_keys();\fR
\fB       (Type :: dgram | seqpacket | stream, InfoKeys) -> ok\fR
\fB           when InfoKeys :: info_keys().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Print information to the erlang shell in table format for a selection of sockets.

.PP
The argument \fIInfoKeys\fR specifies which information is printed for each socket.

.PP
If the first argument is \fIDomain\fR print information for all sockets of that specific \fIdomain/0\fR.

.PP
If the first argument is \fIProto\fR print information for all sockets of that specific \fIprotocol/0\fR.

.PP
If the first argument is \fIType\fR print information for all sockets of that specific \fItype/0\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBinfo() -> info().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Get miscellaneous information about this \fIsocket\fR library.

.PP
The function returns a map with each information item as a key-value pair.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRIn order to ensure data integrity, mutexes are taken when needed. So, don't call this function often.



.RE
.B
\fBinfo(Socket) -> socket_info() when Socket :: socket().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Get miscellaneous info about a socket.

.PP
The function returns a map with each information item as a key-value pair reflecting the "current" state of the socket (such as counter values).

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRIn order to ensure data integrity, mutexes are taken when needed. So, don't call this function often.



.RE
.B
\fBioctl(Socket, GetRequest :: gifconf) ->\fR
\fB               {ok, IFConf :: [#{name := string, addr := sockaddr()}]} |\fR
\fB               {error, Reason}\fR
\fB               when Socket :: socket(), Reason :: posix() | closed;\fR
\fB           (Socket, GetRequest :: nread | nwrite | nspace) ->\fR
\fB               {ok, NumBytes :: non_neg_integer()} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB               when Socket :: socket(), Reason :: posix() | closed;\fR
\fB           (Socket, GetRequest :: atmark) ->\fR
\fB               {ok, Available :: boolean()} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB               when Socket :: socket(), Reason :: posix() | closed;\fR
\fB           (Socket, GetRequest :: tcp_info) ->\fR
\fB               {ok, Info :: map()} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB               when Socket :: socket(), Reason :: posix() | closed.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Set socket (device) parameters.

.PP
This function retrieves a specific parameter, according to the \fIGetRequest\fR argument.

gifconf
.RS 2
Get a list of interface (transport layer) addresses.

.PP
Result; a list of \fImap/0\fRs, one for each interface, with its name and address.


.RE

nread
.RS 2
Get the number of bytes immediately available for reading 
\fI(since OTP 26.1)\fR.
.PP
Result; the number of bytes, \fIinteger/0\fR.


.RE

nwrite
.RS 2
Get the number of bytes in the send queue 
\fI(since OTP 26.1)\fR.
.PP
Result; the number of bytes, \fIinteger/0\fR.


.RE

nspace
.RS 2
Get the free space in the send queue 
\fI(since OTP 26.1)\fR.
.PP
Result; the number of bytes, \fIinteger/0\fR.


.RE

atmark
.RS 2
Test if there is OOB (out-of-bound) data waiting to be read 
\fI(since OTP 26.1)\fR.
.PP
Result; a \fIboolean/0\fR.


.RE

tcp_info
.RS 2
Get miscellaneous TCP related information for a 
\fIconnected\fR socket \fI(since OTP 26.1)\fR.
.PP
Result; a \fImap/0\fR with information items as key-value pairs.


.RE

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRNot all requests are supported by all platforms. To see if a ioctl request is supported on the current platform:

.IP
.nf
	    Request = nread,
	    true = socket:is_supported(ioctl_requests, Request),
	    :

.fi



.RE
.B
\fBioctl(Socket, GetRequest, NameOrIndex) ->\fR
\fB               {ok, Result} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB               when\fR
\fB                   Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                   GetRequest ::\fR
\fB                       gifname | gifindex | gifaddr | gifdstaddr |\fR
\fB                       gifbrdaddr | gifnetmask | gifhwaddr | genaddr |\fR
\fB                       gifmtu | giftxqlen | gifflags | tcp_info,\fR
\fB                   NameOrIndex :: string() | integer(),\fR
\fB                   Result :: dynamic(),\fR
\fB                   Reason :: posix() | closed;\fR
\fB           (Socket, SetRequest, Value) -> ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB               when\fR
\fB                   Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                   SetRequest :: rcvall,\fR
\fB                   Value :: off | on | iplevel,\fR
\fB                   Reason :: posix() | closed;\fR
\fB           (Socket, SetRequest, Value) -> ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB               when\fR
\fB                   Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                   SetRequest :: rcvall_igmpmcast | rcvall_mcast,\fR
\fB                   Value :: off | on,\fR
\fB                   Reason :: posix() | closed.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Get or set socket (device) parameters.

.PP
This function retrieves a specific parameter, according to one of the following \fIGetRequest\fR arguments. The third argument is the (lookup) "key", identifying the interface, for most requests the name of the interface as a \fIstring/0\fR. Also, see the note above.

gifname
.RS 2
Get the name of the interface with the specified index (
\fIinteger/0\fR).
.PP
Result; the name of the interface, \fIstring/0\fR.


.RE

gifindex
.RS 2
Get the index of the interface with the specified name.

.PP
Result; the interface index, \fIinteger/0\fR.


.RE

gifaddr
.RS 2
Get the address of the interface with the specified name.

.PP
Result; the address of the interface, \fIsockaddr/0\fR.


.RE

gifdstaddr
.RS 2
Get the destination address of the point-to-point interface with the specified name.

.PP
Result; the destination address of the interface, \fIsockaddr/0\fR.


.RE

gifbrdaddr
.RS 2
Get the broadcast address of the interface with the specified name.

.PP
Result; broadcast address of the interface, \fIsockaddr/0\fR.


.RE

gifnetmask
.RS 2
Get the network mask of the interface with the specified name.

.PP
Result; the network mask of the interface, \fIsockaddr/0\fR.


.RE

gifhwaddr | genaddr
.RS 2
Get the hardware address for the interface with the specified name.

.PP
Result; the hardware address of the interface, \fIsockaddr/0\fR | \fIbinary/0\fR. The family field contains the 'ARPHRD' device type (or an integer).


.RE

gifmtu
.RS 2
Get the MTU (Maximum Transfer Unit) for the interface with the specified name.

.PP
Result; MTU of the interface, \fIinteger/0\fR.


.RE

giftxqlen
.RS 2
Get the transmit queue length of the interface with the specified name.

.PP
Result; transmit queue length of the interface, \fIinteger/0\fR.


.RE

gifflags
.RS 2
Get the active flag word of the interface with the specified name.

.PP
Result; the active flag word of the interface, is a list of \fIioctl_device_flag/0\fR \fI|\fR \fIinteger( )\fR.


.RE

.PP
With the following \fISetRequest\fR argument this function sets the \fIValue\fR for the request parameter \fI(since OTP 26.1)\fR.

rcvall
.RS 2
Enables (or disables) a socket to receive all IPv4 or IPv6 packages passing through a network interface.

.PP
The \fISocket\fR has to be one of:

An IPv4 socket
.RS 2
Created with the address domain 
\fIinet\fR, socket type \fIraw\fR and protocol \fIip\fR.

.RE

An IPv6 socket
.RS 2
Created with the address domain 
\fIinet6\fR, socket type \fIraw\fR and protocol \fIipv6\fR.

.RE

.PP
The socket must also be bound to an (explicit) local IPv4 or IPv6 interface (\fIany\fR isn't allowed).

.PP
Setting this IOCTL requires elevated privileges.


.RE

.PP
With the following \fISetRequest\fR arguments this function sets the \fIValue\fR for the request parameter \fI(since OTP 26.1)\fR.

rcvall_igmpmcall
.RS 2
Enables (or disables) a socket to receive IGMP multicast IP traffic, 
\fIwithout\fR receiving any other IP traffic.
.PP
The socket has to be created with the address domain \fIinet\fR, socket type \fIraw\fR and protocol \fIigmp\fR.

.PP
The socket must also be bound to an (explicit) local interface (\fIany\fR isn't allowed).

.PP
The receive buffer must be sufficiently large.

.PP
Setting this IOCTL requires elevated privileges.


.RE

rcvall_mcall
.RS 2
Enables (or disables) a socket to receive all multicast IP traffic (as in; all IP packets destined for IP addresses in the range 224.0.0.0 to 239.255.255.255).

.PP
The socket has to be created with the address domain \fIinet\fR, socket type \fIraw\fR and protocol \fIudp\fR.

.PP
The socket must also be bound to an (explicit) local interface (\fIany\fR isn't allowed), And bound to port \fI0\fR.

.PP
The receive buffer must be sufficiently large.

.PP
Setting this IOCTL requires elevated privileges.


.RE


.RE
.B
\fBioctl(Socket, SetRequest, Name, Value) -> ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB               when\fR
\fB                   Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                   SetRequest ::\fR
\fB                       sifflags | sifaddr | sifdstaddr | sifbrdaddr |\fR
\fB                       sifnetmask | sifhwaddr | sifmtu | siftxqlen,\fR
\fB                   Name :: string(),\fR
\fB                   Value :: dynamic(),\fR
\fB                   Reason :: posix() | closed.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Set socket (device) parameters.

.PP
This function sets a specific parameter, according to the \fISetRequest\fR argument. The \fIName\fR argument is the name of the interface, and the \fIValue\fR argument is the value to set.

.PP
These operations require elevated privileges.

sifflags
.RS 2
Set the the active flag word, 
\fI#{Flag => boolean()}\fR, of the interface with the specified name.
.PP
Each flag to be changed should be added to the value \fImap/0\fR, with the value \fItrue\fR if the \fIFlag\fR should be set and \fIfalse\fR if the flag should be cleared.


.RE

sifaddr
.RS 2
Set the address, 
\fIsockaddr/0\fR, of the interface with the specified name.

.RE

sifdstaddr
.RS 2
Set the destination address, 
\fIsockaddr/0\fR, of a point-to-point interface with the specified name.

.RE

sifbrdaddr
.RS 2
Set the broadcast address, 
\fIsockaddr/0\fR, of the interface with the specified name.

.RE

sifnetmask
.RS 2
Set the network mask, 
\fIsockaddr/0\fR, of the interface with the specified name.

.RE

sifhwaddr
.RS 2
Set the hardware address, 
\fIsockaddr/0\fR, of the interface with the specified name.

.RE

sifmtu
.RS 2
Set the MTU (Maximum Transfer Unit), 
\fIinteger/0\fR, for the interface with the specified name.

.RE

siftxqlen
.RS 2
Set the transmit queue length, 
\fIinteger/0\fR, of the interface with the specified name.

.RE


.RE
.B
\fBis_supported(Key1 :: term()) -> boolean().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Check if a socket feature is supported.

.PP
Returns \fItrue\fR if \fIsupports/0\fR has a \fI{Key1, true}\fR tuple or a \fI{Key1, list()}\fR tuple in its returned list, otherwise \fIfalse\fR (also for unknown keys).

.PP
Example:

.IP
.nf
true = socket:is_supported(local),

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBis_supported(Key1 :: term(), Key2 :: term()) -> boolean().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Check if a socket feature is supported.

.PP
Returns \fItrue\fR if \fIsupports(Key1)\fR has a \fI{Key2, true}\fR tuple in its returned list, otherwise \fIfalse\fR (also for unknown keys).

.PP
Example:

.IP
.nf
true = socket:is_supported(msg_flags, errqueue),

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBlisten(Socket :: socket()) ->\fR
\fB                ok | {error, Reason :: posix() | closed}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Make a socket listen for connections.

.PP
Equivalent to \fIlisten(Socket, Backlog)\fR with a default value for \fIBacklog\fR (currently \fI5\fR).


.RE
.B
\fBlisten(Socket, IsServer) -> ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                when\fR
\fB                    Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                    IsServer :: boolean(),\fR
\fB                    Reason :: posix() | closed;\fR
\fB            (Socket, Backlog) -> ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                when\fR
\fB                    Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                    Backlog :: pos_integer(),\fR
\fB                    Reason :: posix() | closed.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Make a socket listen for connections.

.PP
The \fIIsServer\fR clauses are intended to be used for SCTP sockets. The \fIBacklog\fR argument states the length of the queue for incoming not yet accepted connections. Exactly how that number is interpreted is up to the OS' protocol stack, but the resulting effective queue length will most probably be perceived as at least that long.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fROn \fIWindows\fR the socket has to be \fIbound\fR.



.RE
.B
\fBmonitor(Socket :: socket()) -> MonitorRef :: reference().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Start a socket monitor.

.PP
If the \fISocket\fR doesn't exist or when later the monitor is triggered, a \fI'DOWN'\fR message is sent to the process that called \fImonitor/1\fR with the following pattern:

.IP
.nf
	    {'DOWN', MonitorRef, socket, Socket, Info}

.fi

.PP
\fIInfo\fR is the termination reason of the socket or \fInosock\fR if \fISocket\fR did not exist when the monitor was started.

.PP
Making several calls to \fIsocket:monitor/1\fR for the same \fISocket\fR is not an error; each call creates an independent monitor instance.


.RE
.B
\fBnumber_of() -> non_neg_integer().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Return the number of active sockets.


.RE
.B
\fBopen(FD :: integer()) -> dynamic().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Equivalent to \fIopen(FD, #{})\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBopen(FD, Opts) -> {ok, Socket} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB              when\fR
\fB                  FD :: integer(),\fR
\fB                  Opts ::\fR
\fB                      #{domain => domain() | integer(),\fR
\fB                        type => type() | integer(),\fR
\fB                        protocol => default | protocol() | integer(),\fR
\fB                        dup => boolean(),\fR
\fB                        debug => boolean(),\fR
\fB                        use_registry => boolean()},\fR
\fB                  Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                  Reason :: posix() | domain | type | protocol;\fR
\fB          (Domain, Type) -> {ok, Socket} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB              when\fR
\fB                  Domain :: domain(),\fR
\fB                  Type :: type() | integer(),\fR
\fB                  Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                  Reason :: posix() | protocol.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Create a socket.

.PP
\fBWith arguments \fR\fB\fIDomain\fR\fR\fB and \fR\fB\fIType\fR\fR

.PP
Equivalent to \fIopen(Domain, Type, default, #{})\fR.

.PP
\fBWith arguments \fR\fB\fIFD\fR\fR\fB and \fR\fB\fIOpts\fR\fR\fB \fR\fB\fI(since OTP 23.0)\fR\fR

.PP
Creates an endpoint for communication (socket) based on an already existing file descriptor that must be a socket. This function attempts to retrieve the file descriptor's \fIdomain\fR, \fItype\fR and \fIprotocol\fR from the system. This is however not possible on all platforms; in that case they should be specified in \fIOpts\fR.

.PP
The \fIOpts\fR argument can provide extra information:

domain
.RS 2
The file descriptor's communication domain. See also

.PP
\fIopen/2,3,4\fR.


.RE

type
.RS 2
The file descriptor's socket type.

.PP
See also \fIopen/2,3,4\fR.


.RE

protocol
.RS 2
The file descriptor's protocol. The atom 
\fIdefault\fR is equivalent to the integer protocol number \fI0\fR which means the default protocol for a given domain and type.
.PP
If the protocol can not be retrieved from the platform for the socket, and \fIprotocol\fR is not specified, the default protocol is used, which may or may not be correct.

.PP
See also \fIopen/2,3,4\fR.


.RE

dup
.RS 2
If 
\fIfalse\fR don't duplicate the provided file descriptor.
.PP
Defaults to \fItrue\fR; do duplicate the file descriptor.


.RE

debug
.RS 2
If 
\fItrue\fR enable socket debug logging.
.PP
Defaults to \fIfalse\fR; don't enable socket debug logging.


.RE

use_registry
.RS 2
Enable or disable use of the socket registry for this socket. This overrides the global setting.

.PP
Defaults to the global setting, see \fIuse_registry/1\fR.


.RE

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThis function should be used with care! On some platforms it is \fInecessary\fR to provide \fIdomain\fR, \fItype\fR and \fIprotocol\fR since they cannot be retrieved from the platform. On some platforms it is not easy to get hold of a file descriptor to use in this function.



.RE
.B
\fBopen(Domain, Type, Opts | Protocol) ->\fR
\fB              {ok, Socket} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB              when\fR
\fB                  Domain :: domain() | integer(),\fR
\fB                  Type :: type() | integer(),\fR
\fB                  Opts :: map(),\fR
\fB                  Protocol :: default | protocol() | integer(),\fR
\fB                  Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                  Reason :: posix() | protocol.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Create a socket.

.PP
\fBWith arguments \fR\fB\fIDomain\fR\fR\fB, \fR\fB\fIType\fR\fR\fB and \fR\fB\fIProtocol\fR\fR

.PP
Equivalent to \fIopen(Domain, Type, Protocol, #{})\fR.

.PP
\fBWith arguments \fR\fB\fIDomain\fR\fR\fB, \fR\fB\fIType\fR\fR\fB and \fR\fB\fIOpts\fR\fR\fB \fR\fB\fI(since OTP 24.0)\fR\fR

.PP
Equivalent to \fIopen(Domain, Type, default, #{})\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBopen(Domain, Type, Protocol, Opts) ->\fR
\fB              {ok, Socket} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB              when\fR
\fB                  Domain :: domain() | integer(),\fR
\fB                  Type :: type() | integer(),\fR
\fB                  Protocol :: default | protocol() | integer(),\fR
\fB                  Opts ::\fR
\fB                      #{netns => string(),\fR
\fB                        debug => boolean(),\fR
\fB                        use_registry => boolean()},\fR
\fB                  Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                  Reason :: posix() | protocol.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Create a socket.

.PP
Creates an endpoint for communication (socket).

.PP
\fIDomain\fR and \fIType\fR may be \fIinteger/0\fRs, as defined in the platform's header files. The same goes for \fIProtocol\fR as defined in the platform's \fIservices(5)\fR database. See also the OS man page for the library call \fIsocket(2)\fR.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRFor some combinations of \fIDomain\fR and \fIType\fR the platform has got a default protocol that can be selected with \fIProtocol = default\fR, and the platform may allow or require selecting the default protocol, or a specific protocol. Examples:

socket:open(inet, stream, tcp)
.RS 2
It is common that for protocol domain and type 
\fIinet,stream\fR it is allowed to select the \fItcp\fR protocol although that mostly is the default.

.RE
socket:open(local, dgram)
.RS 2
It is common that for the protocol domain 
\fIlocal\fR it is mandatory to not select a protocol, that is; to select the default protocol.

.RE


.PP
The \fIOpts\fR argument is intended for "other" options. The supported option(s) are described below:

netns: string()
.RS 2
Used to set the network namespace during the open call. Only supported on Linux.


.RE

debug: boolean()
.RS 2
Enable or disable debug logging.

.PP
