.RS
.PP
Receive data on a connected socket.

.PP
The argument \fILength\fR specifies the size of the receive buffer. Packet oriented sockets truncate the packet if the size is too small.

.PP
If \fILength == 0\fR; a default buffer size is used, which can be set by \fIsocket:setopt(Socket, {otp,recvbuf}, BufSz)\fR.

.PP
For a socket of type \fIstream\fR, when a \fITimeout\fR argument is used, the operation iterates until \fILength\fR bytes has been received, or the operation times out.  If \fILength == 0\fR all readily available data is returned.

.PP
On a \fIselect\fR system, when the default receive buffer size option \fI{otp,recvbuf}\fR special value \fI{N,BufSize}\fR is used, \fIN\fR limits how many \fIBufSize\fR buffers that may be received in a tight loop before the receive operation returns.  The option value \fI{1,BufSize}\fR is equivalent to just specifying a size value \fIBufSize\fR.

.PP
The message \fIFlags\fR may be symbolic \fImsg_flag/0\fRs and/or \fIinteger/0\fRs as in the platform's appropriate header files. The values of all symbolic flags and integers are or:ed together.

.PP
When there is a socket error this function returns \fI{error, Reason}\fR, or if some data arrived before the error; \fI{error, {Reason, Data}}\fR (can only happen for a socket of type \fIstream\fR).

.PP
If the \fITimeout\fR argument is \fIinfinity\fR; waits for the data to arrive. For a socket of type \fIstream\fR this call won't return until \fIall\fR requested data can be delivered, or if "all available" was requested when the first data chunk arrives, or if the OS reports an error for the operation.

.PP
If the \fITimeout\fR argument is a time-out value (\fInon_neg_integer/0\fR); return \fI{error, timeout}\fR if no data has arrived after \fITimeout\fR milliseconds, or \fI{error, {timeout, Data}}\fR if some but not enough data has been received on a socket of type \fIstream\fR with Length > 0. It \fIcan\fR also return directly with \fI{ok, Data}\fR (type \fIdgram\fR).

.PP
\fITimeout = 0\fR only polls the OS receive call and doesn't engage the Asynchronous Calls mechanisms.  If no data is immediately available \fI{error, timeout} is returned. \fROn a socket of type \fIstream\fR, \fI{error, {timeout, Data}}\fR is returned if there is an insufficient amount of data immediately available.

.PP
If the \fIHandle\fR argument is \fInowait\fR \fI(since OTP 22.1)\fR, starts an asynchronous call if the operation couldn't be completed immediately.

.PP
If the \fIHandle\fR argument is a \fIselect_handle/0\fR, \fI(since OTP 24.0)\fR, or on \fIWindows\fR, the equivalent \fIcompletion_handle/0\fR \fI(since OTP 26.0)\fR, starts an asynchronous call like for \fInowait\fR.

.PP
See the note Asynchronous Calls at the start of this module reference manual page.

.PP
The possible values for \fICompletionStatus\fR in the completion message are:

{ok, Data}
.RS 2
Complete success; All requested data was read.


.RE
{more, Data}
.RS 2
Partial success; Some, but not all, data was read.


.RE
{error, Reason}
.RS 2
An error occured and no data was read.


.RE

.PP
