After receiving a \fIselect\fR message; call \fIsendmsg/3,4\fR with \fISelectInfo\fR as the \fICont\fR argument, to complete the operation.

.PP
With the arguments \fIData\fR and \fICont\fR, continues the send operation.  \fICont\fR should be the \fISelectInfo\fR returned from the previous \fIsendmsg/2,3,4\fR call.

.PP
\fIData\fR can be a \fIMsg\fR \fImap/0\fR where only the key \fIiov\fR is used, or an \fIerlang:iovec/0\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBsendto(Socket :: socket(), Data :: iodata(), Cont | Dest) ->\fR
\fB                Result\fR
\fB                when\fR
\fB                    Cont :: select_info(),\fR
\fB                    Dest :: sockaddr(),\fR
\fB                    Result ::\fR
\fB                        ok |\fR
\fB                        {ok, RestData} |\fR
\fB                        {error, Reason} |\fR
\fB                        {error, {Reason, RestData}},\fR
\fB                    RestData :: binary(),\fR
\fB                    Reason :: posix() | closed | invalid().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Send data on a socket.

.PP
With argument \fIDest\fR; equivalent to \fIsendto(Socket, Data, Dest, [], infinity)\fR.

.PP
With argument \fICont\fR; equivalent to \fIsendto(Socket, Data, Cont, infinity)\fR \fIsince OTP 24.0\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBsendto(Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB             Data :: iodata(),\fR
\fB             Dest :: sockaddr(),\fR
\fB             Flags :: [msg_flag() | integer()]) ->\fR
\fB                dynamic();\fR
\fB            (Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB             Data :: iodata(),\fR
\fB             Cont :: select_info(),\fR
\fB             Timeout :: timeout() | nowait | (Handle :: select_handle())) ->\fR
\fB                dynamic();\fR
\fB            (Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB             Data :: iodata(),\fR
\fB             Dest :: sockaddr(),\fR
\fB             Timeout ::\fR
\fB                 timeout() |\fR
\fB                 nowait |\fR
\fB                 (Handle :: select_handle() | completion_handle())) ->\fR
\fB                dynamic().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Send data on a socket.

.PP
With arguments \fIDest\fR and \fITimeoutOrHandle\fR; equivalent to \fIsendto(Socket, Data, Dest, [], TimeoutOrHandle)\fR.

.PP
With arguments \fIDest\fR and \fIFlags\fR; equivalent to \fIsendto(Socket, Data, Dest, Flags, infinity)\fR.

.PP
With arguments \fICont\fR and \fITimeoutOrHandle\fR; \fICont\fR must be the \fISelectInfo\fR from the previous \fIsendto/3,4,5\fR call and the send is continued with preprocessed send parameters in the \fISelectInfo\fR. Using this argument variant avoids for example having o validate and encode message flags in every call but the first. \fI(Since OTP 24.0)\fR

.PP
See the last argument (argument 5) of \fIsendto/5\fR for an explanation of \fITimeoutOrHandle\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBsendto(Socket, Data, Dest, Flags, Timeout :: infinity) ->\fR
\fB                ok |\fR
\fB                {ok, RestData} |\fR
\fB                {error, Reason} |\fR
\fB                {error, {Reason, RestData}}\fR
\fB                when\fR
\fB                    Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                    Data :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                    Dest :: sockaddr(),\fR
\fB                    Flags :: [msg_flag() | integer()],\fR
\fB                    RestData :: binary(),\fR
\fB                    Reason :: posix() | closed | invalid();\fR
\fB            (Socket, Data, Dest, Flags, Timeout :: non_neg_integer()) ->\fR
\fB                ok |\fR
\fB                {ok, RestData} |\fR
\fB                {error, Reason | timeout} |\fR
\fB                {error, {Reason | timeout, RestData}}\fR
\fB                when\fR
\fB                    Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                    Data :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                    Dest :: sockaddr(),\fR
\fB                    Flags :: [msg_flag() | integer()],\fR
\fB                    RestData :: binary(),\fR
\fB                    Reason :: posix() | closed | invalid();\fR
\fB            (Socket, Data, Dest, Flags, nowait | Handle) ->\fR
\fB                ok |\fR
\fB                {ok, RestData} |\fR
\fB                {select, SelectInfo} |\fR
\fB                {select, {SelectInfo, RestData}} |\fR
\fB                {completion, CompletionInfo} |\fR
\fB                {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                when\fR
\fB                    Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                    Data :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                    Dest :: sockaddr(),\fR
\fB                    Flags :: [msg_flag() | integer()],\fR
\fB                    Handle :: select_handle() | completion_handle(),\fR
\fB                    RestData :: binary(),\fR
\fB                    SelectInfo :: select_info(),\fR
\fB                    CompletionInfo :: completion_info(),\fR
\fB                    Reason :: posix() | closed | invalid().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Send data on a socket.

.PP
The \fITo\fR argument is the destination address where to send the data. For a connected socket this argument is still passed to the OS call that may ignore the address or return an error.

.PP
See \fIsend/4\fR for a description of the \fIFlags\fR and \fIData\fR arguments, and the return values.

.PP
If the \fITimeout\fR argument is \fIinfinity\fR; wait for the OS to complete the send operation (take responsibility for the data), or return an error.

.PP
If the \fITimeout\fR argument is a time-out value (\fInon_neg_integer/0\fR); return \fI{error, timeout}\fR if no data has been sent within \fITimeout\fR millisecond, or \fI{error, {timeout, RestData}}\fR if some data was sent (accepted by the OS for delivery).  \fIRestData\fR is the tail of the data that hasn't been sent.

.PP
If the \fIHandle\fR argument is \fInowait\fR \fI(since OTP 22.1)\fR, starts an asynchronous call if the operation couldn't be completed immediately.

.PP
If the \fIHandle\fR argument is a \fIselect_handle/0\fR, \fI(since OTP 24.0)\fR, or on \fIWindows\fR, the equivalent \fIcompletion_handle/0\fR \fI(since OTP 26.0)\fR, starts an asynchronous call like for \fInowait\fR.

.PP
See the note Asynchronous Calls at the start of this module reference manual page.

.PP
The possible values for \fICompletionStatus\fR in the completion message are:

ok
.RS 2
Complete success; The data was written in its entirety.


.RE
{ok, Written}
.RS 2
Partial success; Some but not all data was written, but no error was reported. 
\fIWritten\fR is the number of bytes that was written.

.RE
{error, Reason}
.RS 2
An error occured and no data was sent.


.RE

.PP
After receiving a \fIselect\fR message; call \fIsendto/3,4\fR with \fISelectInfo\fR as the \fICont\fR argument, to complete the operation.


.RE
.B
\fBsendv(Socket, IOV, Timeout :: infinity) ->\fR
\fB               ok |\fR
\fB               {ok, RestIOV} |\fR
\fB               {error, Reason} |\fR
\fB               {error, {Reason, RestIOV}}\fR
\fB               when\fR
\fB                   Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                   IOV :: erlang:iovec(),\fR
\fB                   RestIOV :: erlang:iovec(),\fR
\fB                   Reason :: posix() | closed | invalid();\fR
\fB           (Socket, IOV, Timeout :: non_neg_integer()) ->\fR
\fB               ok |\fR
\fB               {ok, RestIOV} |\fR
\fB               {error, Reason} |\fR
\fB               {error, {Reason, RestIOV}}\fR
\fB               when\fR
\fB                   Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                   IOV :: erlang:iovec(),\fR
\fB                   RestIOV :: erlang:iovec(),\fR
\fB                   Reason :: posix() | closed | invalid() | timeout;\fR
\fB           (Socket, IOV, nowait | Handle) ->\fR
\fB               ok |\fR
\fB               {ok, RestIOV} |\fR
\fB               {select, SelectInfo} |\fR
\fB               {select, {SelectInfo, RestIOV}} |\fR
\fB               {completion, CompletionInfo} |\fR
\fB               {completion, {CompletionInfo, RestIOV}} |\fR
\fB               {error, Reason} |\fR
\fB               {error, {Reason, RestIOV}}\fR
\fB               when\fR
\fB                   Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                   IOV :: erlang:iovec(),\fR
\fB                   Handle :: select_handle() | completion_handle(),\fR
\fB                   RestIOV :: erlang:iovec(),\fR
\fB                   SelectInfo :: select_info(),\fR
\fB                   CompletionInfo :: completion_info(),\fR
\fB                   Reason :: posix() | closed | invalid();\fR
\fB           (Socket, IOV, Cont) ->\fR
\fB               ok |\fR
\fB               {ok, RestIOV} |\fR
\fB               {error, Reason} |\fR
\fB               {error, {Reason, RestIOV}}\fR
\fB               when\fR
\fB                   Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                   IOV :: erlang:iovec(),\fR
\fB                   Cont :: select_info(),\fR
\fB                   RestIOV :: erlang:iovec(),\fR
\fB                   Reason :: posix() | closed | invalid().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Send \fIerlang:iovec/0\fR data on a connected socket.

.PP
See \fIsendmsg/4\fR about how the \fIIOV\fR data is handled towards the platform's network layer.

.PP
The return value indicates the result from the platform's network layer:

ok
.RS 2
All data has been accepted by the OS for delivery.


.RE

{ok, RestIOV}
.RS 2
Some but not all data was accepted, but no error was reported (partially successful send).  
\fIRestIOV\fR is the tail of \fIIOV\fR that wasn't accepted.

.RE

{error, Reason}
.RS 2
An error has been reported and no data was accepted for delivery.  
\fIReason :: posix/0\fR is what the platform's network layer reported.  \fIclosed\fR means that this socket library was informed that the socket was closed, and \fIinvalid/0\fR means that this socket library found an argument to be invalid.

.RE

{error, {Reason, RestIOV}}
.RS 2
- An error was reported but before that some data was accepted for delivery. 
\fIRestIOV\fR is the tail of \fIIOV\fR that wasn't accepted. See \fI{error, Reason}\fR above.

.RE

.PP
If the \fITimeout\fR argument is \fIinfinity\fR; wait for the OS to complete the send operation (take responsibility for the data), or return an error.

.PP
If the \fITimeout\fR argument is a time-out value (\fInon_neg_integer/0\fR); return \fI{error, timeout}\fR if no data has been sent within \fITimeout\fR millisecond, or \fI{error, {timeout, RestIOV}}\fR if some data was sent (accepted by the OS for delivery).  \fIRestIOV\fR is the tail of the data that hasn't been sent.

.PP
If the \fIHandle\fR argument is \fInowait\fR, starts an asynchronous call if the operation couldn't be completed immediately.

.PP
If the \fIHandle\fR argument is a \fIselect_handle/0\fR, or on \fIWindows\fR, the equivalent \fIcompletion_handle/0\fR, starts an asynchronous call like for \fInowait\fR.

.PP
See the note Asynchronous Calls at the start of this module reference manual page.

.PP
The possible values for \fICompletionStatus\fR in the completion message are:

ok
.RS 2
Complete success; The I/O vector was written in its entirety.


.RE
{ok, Written}
.RS 2
Partial success; Some but not all data was written, but no error was reported. 
\fIWritten\fR is the number of bytes that was written. \fIrest_iov(Written, IOV)\fR can be used to calculate the rest I/O vector (from the original IOV).

.RE
{error, Reason}
.RS 2
An error occured and no data was sent.


.RE

.PP
With the argument \fICont\fR, equivalent to \fIsendv(Socket, IOV, Cont, infinity)\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBsendv(Socket, IOV, Cont, Timeout :: infinity) ->\fR
\fB               ok |\fR
\fB               {ok, RestIOV} |\fR
\fB               {error, Reason} |\fR
\fB               {error, {Reason, RestIOV}}\fR
\fB               when\fR
\fB                   Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                   IOV :: erlang:iovec(),\fR
\fB                   Cont :: select_info(),\fR
\fB                   RestIOV :: erlang:iovec(),\fR
\fB                   Reason :: posix() | closed | invalid();\fR
\fB           (Socket, IOV, Cont, Timeout :: non_neg_integer()) ->\fR
\fB               ok |\fR
\fB               {ok, RestIOV} |\fR
\fB               {error, Reason} |\fR
\fB               {error, {Reason | RestIOV}}\fR
\fB               when\fR
\fB                   Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                   IOV :: erlang:iovec(),\fR
\fB                   Cont :: select_info(),\fR
\fB                   RestIOV :: erlang:iovec(),\fR
\fB                   Reason :: posix() | closed | invalid() | timeout;\fR
\fB           (Socket, IOV, Cont, nowait | SelectHandle) ->\fR
\fB               ok |\fR
\fB               {ok, RestIOV} |\fR
\fB               {select, SelectInfo} |\fR
\fB               {select, {SelectInfo, RestIOV}} |\fR
\fB               {error, Reason} |\fR
\fB               {error, {Reason, RestIOV}}\fR
\fB               when\fR
\fB                   Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                   IOV :: erlang:iovec(),\fR
\fB                   Cont :: select_info(),\fR
\fB                   SelectHandle :: select_handle(),\fR
\fB                   RestIOV :: erlang:iovec(),\fR
\fB                   SelectInfo :: select_info(),\fR
\fB                   Reason :: posix() | closed | invalid().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Send data on a connected socket, continuation.

.PP
Continues sending data on a connected socket. \fICont\fR is the \fISelectInfo\fR returned from the previous \fIsendv/2,3\fR call. \fIIOV\fR should be the rest data that wasn't sent.

.PP
See asynchronous calls about continuing unfinished calls.

.PP
See \fIsendv/3\fR about the return values.


.RE
.B
\fBsetopt(Socket, SocketOption, Value) ->\fR
\fB                ok | {error, invalid() | closed}\fR
\fB                when\fR
\fB                    Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                    SocketOption ::\fR
\fB                        {Level :: otp, Opt :: otp_socket_option()},\fR
\fB                    Value :: dynamic();\fR
\fB            (Socket, SocketOption, Value) ->\fR
\fB                ok | {error, posix() | invalid() | closed}\fR
\fB                when\fR
\fB                    Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                    SocketOption :: socket_option(),\fR
\fB                    Value :: dynamic().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Set a socket option.

.PP
Set an OS protocol level option, or an \fIotp\fR pseudo protocol level option. The latter level is this module's implementation level above the OS protocol levels.

.PP
See the type otp_socket_option()  for a description of the \fIotp\fR protocol level.

.PP
See the type \fIsocket_option/0\fR for which OS protocol level options that this implementation knows about, how they are related to OS option names, and if there are known peculiarities with any of them.

.PP
What options that are valid depends on the OS, and on the kind of socket (\fIdomain/0\fR,\fItype/0\fR and \fIprotocol/0\fR).  See the type \fIsocket_option()\fR and the socket options  chapter in the User's Guide for more info.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRNot all options are valid, nor possible to set, on all platforms. That is, even if this \fIsocket\fR implementation  support an option; it doesn't mean that the underlying OS does.



.RE
.B
\fBsetopt(socket(), Level :: term(), Opt :: term(), Value :: term()) ->\fR
\fB                _.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Set a socket option \fI(backwards compatibility function)\fR.

.PP
Equivalent to \fIsetopt(Socket, {Level, Opt}, Value)\fR, or as a special case if \fIOpt = NativeOpt ::\fR \fIinteger/0\fR and \fIValue =\fR \fIbinary/0\fR equivalent to \fIsetopt_native(Socket, {Level, NativeOpt}, ValueSpec)\fR.

.PP
Use \fIsetopt/3\fR or \fIsetopt_native/3\fR instead to handle the option level and name as a single term, and to make the difference between known options and native options clear.


.RE
.B
\fBsetopt_native(Socket, Option, Value) ->\fR
\fB                       ok | {error, posix() | invalid() | closed}\fR
\fB                       when\fR
\fB                           Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                           Option ::\fR
\fB                               socket_option() |\fR
\fB                               {Level, NativeOpt} |\fR
\fB                               {NativeLevel, NativeOpt},\fR
\fB                           Value :: native_value(),\fR
\fB                           Level :: level(),\fR
\fB                           NativeLevel :: integer(),\fR
\fB                           NativeOpt :: integer().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Set a "native" socket option.

.PP
Sets a socket option that may be unknown to our implementation, or that has a type not compatible with our implementation, that is; in "native mode".

.PP
If \fIValue\fR is an \fIinteger/0\fR it will be used as a \fIC\fR type \fI(int)\fR, if it is a \fIboolean/0\fR it will be used as a \fIC\fR type \fI(int)\fR with the \fIC\fR implementations values for \fIfalse\fR or \fItrue\fR, and if it is a \fIbinary/0\fR its content and size will be used as the option value.

.PP
The socket option may be specified with an ordinary \fIsocket_option/0\fR tuple, with a symbolic \fILevel\fR as \fI{\fR\fILevel :: level/0\fR\fI, \fR\fINativeOpt :: integer/0\fR\fI}\fR, or with integers for both \fINativeLevel\fR and \fINativeOpt\fR as \fI{\fR\fINativeLevel :: integer/0\fR\fI, \fR\fINativeOpt :: integer/0\fR\fI}\fR.

.PP
If an option is valid depends both on the platform and on what kind of socket it is (\fIdomain/0\fR, \fItype/0\fR and \fIprotocol/0\fR).

.PP
The integer values for \fINativeLevel\fR and \fINativeOpt\fR as well as the \fIValue\fR encoding has to be deduced from the header files for the running system.


.RE
.B
\fBshutdown(Socket, How) -> ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                  when\fR
\fB                      Socket :: socket(),\fR
\fB                      How :: read | write | read_write,\fR
\fB                      Reason :: posix() | closed.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Shut down all or part of a full-duplex connection.


.RE
.B
\fBsockname(Socket :: socket()) -> {ok, SockAddr} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                  when\fR
\fB                      SockAddr :: sockaddr_recv(),\fR
\fB                      Reason :: posix() | closed.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Get the socket's address.

.PP
Returns the address to which the socket is currently bound. If the bind address had the wildcard port \fI0\fR, the address returned by this function contains the ephemeral port selected by the OS.


.RE
.B
\fBsocknames(Socket :: socket(), AssocId :: sctp_assoc_id()) ->\fR
\fB                   {ok, [SockAddr]} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                   when\fR
\fB                       SockAddr :: sockaddr_recv(),\fR
\fB                       Reason :: posix() | closed.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Get the socket's address.

.PP
Returns all the locally bound addresses to which the socket is currently bound.

.PP
If the socket is IPv4 then all returned addresess will be IPv4. If the socket is IPv6, then the returned addresess can be a mix of IPv4 and IPv6.

.PP
For a one-to-many socket, AssocId specifies the association. For a one-to-one socket, AssocId is ignored.

.PP
If AssocId is 0 (zero), then the returned addresses are without any particular association.


.RE
.B
\fBsupports() ->\fR
\fB                  [{Key1 :: term(),\fR
\fB                    boolean() |\fR
\fB                    [{Key2 :: term(),\fR
\fB                      boolean() | [{Key3 :: term(), boolean()}]}]}].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Retrieve information about what socket features the module and the platform supports.

.PP
Returns a list of, in no particular order, \fI{Key1, \fR\fIsupports(Key1)\fR\fI}\fR tuples for every \fIKey1\fR described in \fIsupports/1\fR, and \fI{Key, boolean()}\fR tuples for each of the following keys:

sctp
.RS 2
SCTP support


.RE

ipv6
.RS 2
IPv6 support


.RE

local
.RS 2
Unix Domain sockets support (
\fIAF_UNIX | AF_LOCAL\fR)

.RE

netns
.RS 2
Network Namespaces support (Linux, 
\fIsetns(2)\fR)

.RE

sendfile
.RS 2
Sendfile support (
\fIsendfile(2)\fR)

.RE


.RE
.B
\fBsupports(Key1 :: term()) ->\fR
\fB                  [{Key2 :: term(),\fR
\fB                    boolean() | [{Key3 :: term(), boolean()}]}].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Retrieve information about what socket features the module and the platform supports.

.PP
If \fIKey1 = msg_flags\fR returns a list of \fI{Flag, boolean()}\fR tuples for every \fIFlag\fR in \fImsg_flag/0\fR with the \fIboolean/0\fR indicating if the flag is supported on this platform.

.PP
If \fIKey1 = protocols\fR returns a list of \fI{Name, boolean()}\fR tuples for every \fIName\fR in\fIprotocol/0\fR with the \fIboolean/0\fR indicating if the protocol is supported on this platform.

.PP
If \fIKey1 = options\fR returns a list of \fI{SocketOption, boolean()}\fR tuples for every \fISocketOption\fR in \fIsocket_option/0\fR with the \fIboolean/0\fR indicating if the socket option is supported on this platform.

.PP
There is no particular order of any of the returned lists.

.PP
For other values of \fIKey1\fR returns \fI[]\fR. Note that in future versions of this module or on different platforms, there might be more supported keys.


.RE
.B
\fBsupports(Key1 :: term(), Key2 :: term()) ->\fR
\fB                  [{Key3 :: term(), boolean()}].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Retrieve information about what socket features the module and the platform supports.

.PP
If \fIKey1 = options\fR, for a \fIKey2\fR in \fIlevel/0\fR returns a list of \fI{Opt, boolean()}\fR tuples for all known socket options \fIOpt\fR on that \fILevel = Key2\fR with the \fIboolean/0\fR indicating if the socket option is supported on this platform. See \fIsetopt/3\fR and \fIgetopt/2\fR.

.PP
There is no particular order of any of the returned lists.

.PP
For other values of \fIKey1\fR or \fIKey2\fR returns \fI[]\fR. Note that in future versions of this module or on different platforms, there might be more supported keys.


.RE
.B
\fBuse_registry(D :: boolean()) -> ok.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Set the global \fIuse_registry\fR option default value.

.PP
Globally change if the socket registry is to be used or not. Note that its still possible to override this explicitly when creating an individual sockets, see \fIopen/2,3,4\fR for more info (the \fIOpts :: map/0\fR).


.RE
.B
\fBwhich_sockets() -> [socket()].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Return a list of all known sockets.

.PP
Equivalent to \fIwhich_sockets(fun (_) -> true end)\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBwhich_sockets(FilterRule) -> [socket()]\fR
\fB                       when\fR
\fB                           FilterRule ::\fR
\fB                               inet | inet6 | local | stream | dgram |\fR
\fB                               seqpacket | sctp | tcp | udp |\fR
\fB                               pid() |\fR
\fB                               fun((socket_info()) -> boolean()).\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Return a filtered list of known sockets.

.PP
There are several predefined \fIFilterRule\fRs and one general:

inet | inet6
.RS 2
Only the sockets with matching 
\fIdomain/0\fR are returned.

.RE

stream | dgram | seqpacket
.RS 2
Only the sockets with matching 
\fItype/0\fR are returned.

.RE

sctp | tcp | udp
.RS 2
Only the sockets with matching 
\fIprotocol/0\fR are returned.

.RE

pid/0
.RS 2
Only the sockets with matching Controlling Process are returned. See the OTP socket option 
\fIcontrolling_process\fR.

.RE

fun((socket_info()) -> boolean())
.RS 2
The general filter rule. A fun that takes the socket info and returns a 
\fIboolean/0\fR indicating if the socket should be returned or not.

.RE


.RE
